						<summary>

						<p>Slab kept in the Jaina temple.</p>						

						<p>Vikramāditya VI A.D. 1087.</p>						

						<p>This inscription which refers itself to the reign of Tribhuvanamalla is dated in the Chālukya-Vikrama year 12, Prabhava, Pausha ba. 14, Vaḍḍavāra, Uttarāyaṇa-saṁkrānti corresponding regularly to A.D. 1087, December 25, Saturday f.d.t. 86.</p>						

						<p>It records a gift of land, houses, etc., made by <hi rend="italic">Mahāprabhu</hi> Nidhiyama-gāvuṇḍa for the benefit of the Jaina temple constructed by him at Koṁḍanūr. The donor belonged to Balātkāragaṇa of Mūla-saṁgha and the genealogical account of the preceptors is narrated at length. The Chālukya prince Jayakarṇa and the Raṭṭa chief Sēna are also eulogized. The record is published in <hi rend="italic">JBBRAS,</hi> Vol. X, pp. 287 ff.</p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
